  "title": "Common Ground Breakdown",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3826cfb1af9c5a71",
      "text": "Fluent communications among humans comes with a paradox. On the constructive side, we continually repair common ground without even noticing we're doing it. On the confusing side, we can completely fail to notice when common ground has broken down."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "49c956d17df9d549",
      "text": "On our turn to speak, we watch the listener closely and adjust our pace or level of detail according to what we think the other person understands. We may notice a wrinkled brow and backtrack to fill in some detail. The speaker and listener may not even notice the backtrack. This is an example of continually repairing common ground, and an example of expertise and fluency. We do this without even noticing."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e8a9fbce09222f9e",
      "text": "When listening we may avoid interruptions to allow the speaker to complete their thoughts fully. Listening includes holding onto moments of ambiguity awaiting further explanation to bring clarity. We don't even notice when the ambiguity gets so big that our brow wrinkles."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a3a3a50e1e761abf",
      "text": "Fundamental common ground breakdown happens often. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "79656c572085ada7",
      "text": "Alice and Bob are experts in different parts of the system and diagnosing some symptoms together. Alice assumes Bob knows about XYZ. Bob knows nothing about it—doesn't even know to ask questions about it. As Bob does not wrinkle his brow nor ask questions, Alice fluently continues without sharing details about XYZ. Both Alice and Bob feel like they are communicating with common ground and the critical gap in understanding about XYZ goes unnoticed."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "34ab89005acd780b",
      "text": "In hindsight, we might say Alice should not have assumed Bob knew. Or we might say Bob should have known. Either of those claims only work in hindsight."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "98496c86f45f20d6",
      "text": "When Alice is communicating with Cindy, who does also know about XYZ, the communications are more effective by skipping over details about XYZ to focus attention on other areas of confusion. For Alice, the absence of wrinkled brow in Cindy is indistinguishable from the absence of wrinkled brow in Bob."
    },
